a. Create a data frame that is a subset of the Teams data frame that contains only the years from 2000 through 2009 and the variables yearID, W, and L.

Teams_subset <- Teams %>% select(yearID,W,L) %>% filter(yearID >= 2000 & yearID <= 2009)

b. How many years did the Chicago Cubs (teamID is CHN) hit at least 200 HRs in a season and what was the median number of wins in those seasons.

There are 7 years in which the Chicago Cubs hit at least 200 HRs in a season. The median number of wins in those seasons is 84 wins.

HR200years <- Teams %>% filter(teamID == "CHN" & HR >= 200) %>% nrow()

HR200year_median <- Teams %>% filter(teamID == "CHN" & HR >= 200) %>% summarise(median_wins = median(W))

c. Make a line plot of total home runs per season and stratify by league. (Remove observations where league is missing.) Comment on anything interesting that you observe.

One interesting thing that I observed is that initially there were more leagues than just the American League and the National League. I also wasnt aware that there was such a large increase in the number of home runs starting around 1920.

leagues <- Teams %>% group_by(lgID, na.rm = TRUE)

ggplot(leagues, aes(x = yearID, y = HR)) +
  geom_line() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Total Home Runs per Season") + facet_wrap(~lgID)

ggplot(leagues, aes(x = yearID, y = HR, color=lgID)) +
  geom_line() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Total Home Runs per Season")

d. Create an indicator variable called winning record which is defined as TRUE if the number of wins is greater than the number of losses and FALSE otherwise. Plot a scatter plot Runs (R) vs Runs against (RA) with the color of each point showing whether that team had a winning record or not.

W_record <- Teams %>% mutate(WinningRecord = W > L)

ggplot(data = W_record, aes(x = R, y = RA)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = WinningRecord),size = 0.7)

f. Create a categorical variable with 4 levels: before 1900, 1900 - 1949, 1950-1999, 2000 or later. (Hint: There is a function called cut that will help you here.) Use this as the color of the point in the scatterplot of strikeouts vs walks that you created in the previous problem.

Years <- min(Teams$yearID):max(Teams$yearID)
first_year <- min(Teams$yearID)
last_year <- max(Teams$yearID)

Teams$YearInterval <- cut(Teams$yearID, 
                  breaks = c(0,1899,1950,1999,last_year),
                  labels = c("Before 1900","1900-1949","1950-1999","2000 or Later"))

ggplot(data = Teams, aes(x = SO, y = BB,color=YearInterval)) + geom_point(size=0.3) + xlab("Strikeouts (SO)") + ylab("Walks (BB)")

a. What month had the highest proportion of cancelled flights? What month had the lowest? Interpret any seasonal patterns.

February had the highest proportion of cancelled flights and November had the lowest. I was expecting there to be a more distinct seasonal pattern. It makes sense that February has a high proportion of cancelled flights, considering the weather. However, June and July also have high proportions of cancelled flights

month_flights <- flights %>% group_by(month) %>% mutate(cancelled = is.na(air_time)) %>% summarise(CancelledFlights = sum(cancelled == TRUE), TotalFlights = n()) %>% mutate(PropCancelled = CancelledFlights/TotalFlights) %>% arrange(-PropCancelled)

b. Create a histogram of the departure delays times (dep delay) for all flights that had a delay time greater than 0.

#filter to get flights delay time > 0 
DelayFlights <- flights %>% filter(dep_delay > 0) %>% mutate(MonthName = month.name[month])

#add bins parameter to make it look better
ggplot(aes(x = dep_delay), data = DelayFlights) + geom_histogram() + xlab("Departure Delay Times (min)") + ylab("Number of Flights") + xlim(0,400)

d. Create side-by-side boxplots of delay times for flights with delays 60 minutes or greater for the top 5 airlines (in terms of number of flights).

#Get top 5 airlines with highest number of flights

#Finding the top 5 airlines in terms of number of flights
top_airlines <- flights %>% group_by(carrier) %>% summarise(TotalFlights = sum(n())) %>% arrange(-TotalFlights) %>% head(5)%>% select(carrier)

#Filtering flights with delays greater than or equal to 60 min and only by the carriers that are in the top 5
top_airlines_delay <- flights %>% mutate(Top5 = carrier %in% top_airlines$carrier) %>% filter(dep_delay >= 60 & Top5 == TRUE)


ggplot(aes(y=dep_delay,x=carrier), data=top_airlines_delay) + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Number of Flights") + xlab("Carrier")
